    <h2>Sample Trade: A Complete Meme Coin Risk Management Example</h2>

    <p>Let's walk through a real example. You have a $5,000 portfolio and want to trade a new Solana meme coin, "Bonk2.0" (hypothetical). Here's the full plan:</p>

    <ol>
      <li><strong>Portfolio risk:</strong> 1% per trade = $50 max loss</li>
      <li><strong>Stop loss:</strong> 20% below entry (meme coin volatility)</li>
      <li><strong>Position size:</strong> $50 / 20% = $250 (buy at $0.001, stop at $0.0008)</li>
      <li><strong>Take profit Tier 1:</strong> +40% = $0.0014, sell 25% ($62.50 â†�™ $87.50)</li>
      <li><strong>Take profit Tier 2:</strong> +100% = $0.002, sell 35% ($87.50 â†�™ $175)</li>
      <li><strong>Trailing stop on remaining 40%:</strong> Start at entry, trail at 15%</li>
      <li><strong>Best case:</strong> Coin 10x, remaining 40% catches it = $1,000 profit on $250 risk</li>
      <li><strong>Worst case:</strong> Stop hits at 20% loss = -$50</li>
    </ol>

    <p>This is a trade you can sleep on. The math works out regardless of what happens. You risk $50 to potentially make $1,000+ while guaranteeing you don't blow up your portfolio.</p>

    <div class="highlight-box">
      <p><strong>Bottom Line:</strong> Crypto trading without stop losses and take profit orders is like driving without brakes. You might have a great ride for a while, but when something goes wrong, you crash hard. Set your levels, stick to your plan, and let the market do the rest. Your future self - the one who didn't ride a 100x gain all the way back to zero - will thank you.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <h3>What percentage should I set my stop loss at for meme coins?</h3>
    <p>For high-volatility meme coins, a 20-25% stop loss is standard. Low-volatility blue chips like Bitcoin or ETH can use tighter 5-8% stops. Always adjust based on the specific coin's Average True Range (ATR).</p>

    <h3>Can I set stop losses on Solana DEXs?</h3>
    <p>Yes. Jupiter (jup.ag) now offers limit order and DCA functionality that can act as stop losses and take profit orders. For other DEXs like Raydium and Orca, you'll need to use third-party tools or manually monitor your positions.</p>

    <h3>Should I use a market or limit stop loss?</h3>
    <p>Use market stop losses for highly volatile meme coins where execution speed matters more than price precision. Use limit stop losses for larger-cap coins where you want to control the fill price.</p>

    <h3>What's the best risk/reward ratio for crypto trading?</h3>
    <p>Aim for a minimum of 1:2 (risk $1 to make $2). Experienced meme coin traders often target 1:3 or higher to account for the lower win rate associated with high-volatility assets.</p>

    <h3>How often should I adjust my stop loss?</h3>
    <p>Move your stop loss tighter as the trade moves in your favor. Check your positions once or twice daily. Never widen your stop loss - that defeats the purpose of risk management.</p>

    
